    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "hospital with fever and cough in the last 2 days, and his highest body temperature was 38.3\u00b0C before admission. The laboratory examinations showed decreased white blood cell count (2.50 \u00d7 10 9 /L) and elevated C-reactive protein (16.2 mg/L; normal range 0-10 mg/L).",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "Non-contrast-enhanced chest computed tomography (CT) (Fig. 1a, b) showed multiple, bilateral, peripheral, patchy ground glass opacities, lobular, and subsegmental, with fading margins. The lesions had mainly a subpleural distribution.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 53,
                    "end": 65,
                    "text": "(Fig. 1a, b)",
                    "ref_id": "FIGREF0"
                }
            ],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "CT also demonstrated slight thickening of the adjacent pleura (yellow arrow) and interlobular septa in the lesion (red arrow). Subsequently, the patients had laboratoryconfirmed 2019-nCoV infection by real-time polymerase chain reaction (PCR). After 5 days, CT scan (Fig. 1c, d) showed enlarged lesions, compared with previous images, and progressive ground glass opacities in both lower lobes, indicating disease progression.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 266,
                    "end": 278,
                    "text": "(Fig. 1c, d)",
                    "ref_id": "FIGREF0"
                }
            ],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "Infection with 2019-nCoV was confirmed based on the patient's epidemiological history, clinical manifestations, imaging characteristics, and laboratory tests.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "Bilateral, multiple, patchy, or ground glass opacities, with subpleural distribution, were the lung CT appearances of this patient, affected by 2019-nCoV pneumonia. These characteristics should be recognized by professionals working in imaging departments.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
